Believers in Free Trade
- Cambridge - Recently, I was invited as a guest speaker for a globalization course taught by two Harvard colleagues. "I must warn you,"
one of them warned me beforehand, saying, "These students are strong advocates of globalization."
He had asked the students in the first class to choose between free trade and import restrictions, and more than 90% favored the former.
And this was before any mention of the magical effects of comparative advantage.
Know that in real surveys asking the same questions to representative samples — rather than Harvard students — would yield a completely different result.
In the US, opponents of trade restrictions outnumber supporters by 2:1.
But the answers from Harvard students are not particularly surprising.
Because those with higher technical skills and better education tend to be more supportive of free trade than blue-collar workers.
Perhaps these Harvard students have already had expectations about their (future) prospects and made decisions accordingly.
Or perhaps they don't actually understand how trade works.
After all, when I met with them, I asked the same question in a different form, emphasizing the distributional effects that trade might produce.
The consensus in favor of fair trade vanished even faster than I expected.
I began by asking if everyone agreed that I could perform a very special experiment.
I picked Nicholas and John as volunteers, then told them that I had a way to make $200 disappear from Nicholas's account —— boom —— while adding $300 to John's, and that social engineering could make the class as a whole worth an additional $100.
Will they allow me to play this little trick?
The result was that only a small portion firmly agreed, many were hesitant, and even more opposed implementing this change.

Clearly, the students found it hard to tolerate such a large income redistribution, even though the economic pie was being made bigger.
I then asked why, despite this, the majority almost instinctively supported free trade, which also leads to a similar — indeed, often even larger — redistribution of wealth from losers to winners.
Students were clearly taken aback.
I continued, let's assume that Nicholas and John both run competing small businesses.
John works harder, saves more, invests better, and produces a superior product, so he ends up not only with an extra $300 but also driving Nicholas out of business and leaving him $200 in debt.
How many students would support such a shift?
This time, most supported it — in fact, only Nicholas disagreed!
I then proposed another hypothesis directly related to international trade.
Would the students agree if John ousted Nicholas by importing high-quality products from Germany?
Or by outsourcing his business processes to China, where labor rights are less developed?
Or by employing child labor in Indonesia?
The agreement would decline in accordance with the options listed.
Moreover, technological innovation can lead to the same type of inequality as trade, making some people worse off. What is your stance on this?
Very few students were willing to curb technological advancements.
To virtually everyone, banning light bulbs to save candle makers' jobs is a ridiculous idea.
Therefore, what they oppose is not redistribution per se, but specific forms of it.
Like most of us, they care about the fairness of the process.
If we are to judge the outcomes of redistribution, we need to know the objective context in which they arise.
We do not begrudge Bill Gates or Warren Buffett their vast fortunes, even if their rivals have long fared worse, because they and their competitors operate under the same basic rules and face similar opportunities and challenges.
But if Gates and Buffett had amassed their wealth through fraud, violation of labor laws, environmental destruction, or foreign government subsidies, our attitudes would be quite different.
If we cannot stomach redistribution achieved through violations of the moral standards generally accepted at home, how can we be so complacent about it when it involves cross-border transactions?
Similarly, when we expect that the redistributive effects will achieve equality over the long term and that everyone will benefit in the end, we are unlikely to mind the transfer of income.
This is also why we are willing to promote development despite the short-term negative impacts that technology may have on certain individuals.
On the other hand, when trade continuously hits the same group of people — low-skilled blue-collar workers — we become concerned about globalization.
But many economists ignore these obvious distinctions.
They tend to attribute the unease about globalization to foolish and selfish protectionist motives or ignorance, without realizing that the central issue is actually ethical.
Because they fail to recognize that international trade sometimes — although not always — can lead to redistributive consequences that we would not accept domestically, they cannot properly engage in public discourse.
And how can they defend globalization if it fails on moral grounds?
When globalization occasionally triggers thorny issues related to the legalization of redistribution effects, we should not respond impulsively with trade restrictions.
There are many pros and cons to be weighed, including the possibility that globalization may deprive others elsewhere of wealth more severely than victims in the United States.
But democratic countries should have a more appropriate discussion on this and make conscious and more considered decisions.
Amy persistent infatuation with globalization simply because it makes the pie bigger, on the other hand, will inevitably erode its legitimacy over the long term.
